The exercise is based on survey data which was collected in 2014 from students participating in the statistics course Introduction to Social Statistics. The data contains information on students exam points and attitudes towards statistics and learning.

The dataset has 166 observations (rows) of 7 variables (columns) of which 1 is character and 6 numerical. There are no missing values. Students ages range between 17 and 55 years.

2. Overview of data

The plot matrix visualizes the distributions of the variables (diagonal), and the plotted relationships and correlations between them, for women (in red) and men (in turquoise) separately.

ggpairs(lrn2014, mapping = aes(col = gender, alpha = 0.3), lower = list(continuous = wrap("smooth", alpha = 0.3, size=1.5), combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)), progress = F) +
  theme_bw()

Some observations from the plot: Both the correlations and scatterplots show that a positive relationship appears to exist between students attitudes and their statistics course exam points, i.e.those with a more positive attitude towards learning seem to do better. Mens attitudes seem slightly higher compared to womens.

Looking at the correlations, there is a weak negative correlation between exam points and age, and exam points and scores of surface learning, whereas scores of strategic learning and exam points seem to correlate positively. Moreover, especially for men, scores of deep learning correlate negatively with scores related to surface learning, which seems quite logical.

We can also see that there are more females than males and that despite the wide age range, most of the students are below age 30: the mean age is 26, as can be seen below.

lrn2014$age %>% mean()
## [1] 25.51205

Overall, the exam points of all students vary between a maximum of 33 and minimum on 7 but the density plot and boxplot above suggest the distribution of points is not that normal but instead skewed towards left.

3. Regression model

I choose attitude, strategic learning and surface learning as the explanatory variables of points and fit the following model:

model1 <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = lrn2014)
summary(model1)  # Check model fit

## F-statistic: 14.13 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 3.156e-08

The regression result suggests, that neither strategic nor surface learning have much effect and are not significant predictors of exam points. Only the slope estimate for attitude is significantly different from 0 here. All together, the three variables explain about one fifth of the variation in exam points. I drop the two non-significant explanatory variables and fit a new simple model:

model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = lrn2014)
summary(model2)  # Check model fit
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = lrn2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:

## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

4. Interpretation

The R-squared of the second model is 0.1906, almost the same as in the first model although two explanatory variables were removed. Overall, this model alone does not explain that much, but still around 19% of the variation in exam points is explained by the variation in attitude score. The slope estimate for attitude is 3.5, so by each unit increase in attitude score, the exam result increases by 3.5 points.

Below a scatterplot of the data with the fitted line.

p1 <- lrn2014 %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_point(aes(x = attitude, y = points)) +
  geom_line(aes(x = attitude, y = predict(model2)))

p2 <- qplot(attitude, points, data = lrn2014) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

p1 | p2

5. Diagnostic plots

The linear model assumes normal distribution of residuals. The normal Q-Q plot shows that residuals are more or less normally distributed, but still somewhat diverging from the straight line, especially towards the extremes.

The linear model also assumes equal variance of residuals. The plot of residuals vs fitted values seems quite reasonable and the residuals seem to be spread more or less randomly around the 0 line.

Residuals vs Leverage plot does not indicate any extreme problematic outliers with a high leverage value (?).

3. Selection of predictors

One of the variables is a logical TRUE/FALSE variable on high use of alcohol. This is the target variable of interest in this exercise. To study the relationships between high/low alcohol consumption and some other characteristics I select the following and my hypothesis are:

Sex - I hypothesize that there are more high users among men.

Study time - I hypothesize that those who study more are perhaps more focused and motivated and consequently use less alcohol.

Going out with friends - My hypothesis is that students who go out more consume more alcohol and are thus more likely to be high users.

Extra-curricular activities - Leisure time activities may be associated with a healthier lifestyle and mean there is less time for drinking. I hypothesize that students with extra-curricular activities are less likely to be heavy drinkers.

5. Logistic regression

Logistic regression of my variables as predictors and the binary high/low alcohol consumption variable as the target is fit below, model specified as binomial.

model0 <- glm(high_use ~ sex + studytime + goout + activities, data = alc, family = "binomial")

Of the selected predictors sex, studytime and going out with friends seem to associate significantly with high use of alcohol - the confidence intervals of these variables do not include 1.

Men have two times higher odds of being a high user of alcohol compared to women. Those who study more use less alcohol according to the results: for each point increase in studytime per week the students have 0.64 times lower odds of being a high consumer. Those who go out have higher odds of being high consumers, with a 2.1 times higher odds for each increase in going out score.

6. Predictive power

Fit a new model with the significant predictors only:

model1 <- glm(high_use ~ sex + studytime +  goout, data = alc, family = "binomial")
probabilities <- predict(model1, type = "response") # predicting probability of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

select(alc, high_use, sex, studytime, probability, prediction) %>% tail(10)

For students with high alcohol use (FALSE), the model predicted 234 of them correct, and 25 wrong. For students with high alcohol use (TRUE) the model predicted well 53 and wrong 58.

Calculate proportion of inaccurately classified students. I use the function from the exercise set:

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2243243

Around 22% of the predictions were wrong. Same as (figures from the crosstabulation):

(25+58)/370
## [1] 0.2243243

# Divide dataset to train and test sets

test <- boston_scaled[-ind,] #create test dataset

LDA is a technique used to reduce the number of dimensions in a dataset. In practice, it looks for linear combinations of original variables. Here, three dimensions LD1, LD2 and LD3 are found.

# LDA (bi)plot

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

classes <- as.numeric(train$crime) #crime classes as numeric

plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes) #plot
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)

# K-means clustering
set.seed(13)
km <- kmeans(Boston, centers = 3)
pairs(Boston[1:6], col = km$cluster) #plot Boston dataset with clusters identified with colors

# Optimal number of clusters - total within cluster sum of squares (WCSS)
set.seed(123)
k_max <- 10 #max number of clusters
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(Boston, k)$tot.withinss}) #calculate total within sum of squares by number of clusters
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line') #plot number of clusters and the total WCSS

The optimal number of clusters can be assessed comparing the total within sum of squares for different numbers of clusters. The plot shows the deepest drop in total within sum of squares when passing from 1 to 2.

Lets add the baseline from the original data as a new variable to the summary data (now using the data with the outliers) to fit a linear model using the baseline as an additional control.

# Original data in wide format

# New column
RATSS4 <- RATSS2 %>%
  mutate(baseline = RATS$WD1)

# Fit a linear model with the mean as the response

As a first step lets draw a plot identifying the observations in each treatment group but ignoring the longitudinal nature of the data.

ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = week, y = bprs, linetype = subject, color = treatment)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ treatment, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(BPRSL$bprs), max(BPRSL$bprs)), name = "BPRS") +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Week", breaks = seq(0, 8, 1))

BPRS values show a somewhat declining trend over time but the plot suggests there is little difference between the two treatment groups.

Next a linear model is fitted, still ignoring the repeated-measures structure of the weights in the data.

# Create a regression model BPRS_reg
BPRS_reg <- lm(bprs ~ week + treatment, data = BPRSL)

# print out a summary of the model
summary(BPRS_reg)

Next, a random intercept model is fitted which allows the intercepts of individual men to differ from other men.

# Create a random intercept model
BPRS_ref <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + (1 | subject), data = BPRSL, REML = FALSE)

# Print the summary of the model
summary(BPRS_ref)

The interaction is not significant and the ANOVA test suggests to stay with the previous ref1 model. I use that for plotting.

# Plot the observed values
p1 <- ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = week, y = bprs, linetype = subject, color = treatment)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ treatment, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(BPRSL$bprs), max(BPRSL$bprs)), name = "Observed bprs") +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Week", breaks = seq(0, 8, 1))

# Create a vector of the fitted values
fitted <- fitted(BPRS_ref1)

# Add a new column with fitted values BPRSL
BPRSL <-  BPRSL %>% 
  mutate(fitted = fitted)
